    content: `Stage one: the clip. Something happens. A moment, a quote, a reaction. Someone records it or screenshots it. It gets posted somewhere with a short caption.

Stage two: discovery. A few accounts with actual reach find it. They repost. Their followers repost. The original post hits a number that triggers the platform's recommendation engine. Suddenly the clip is everywhere.

Stage three: peak. This is the 48-hour window where the thing is unavoidable. Every account is posting it. Every podcast is mentioning it. People who don't follow the original person or topic are seeing it. The thing has escaped its original context completely.

Stage four: discourse. Someone posts a take. Someone disagrees. Someone makes a video explaining why the original thing was actually problematic, or actually brilliant, or actually misunderstood. The content about the content outperforms the original content.

Stage five: exhaustion. Everybody has seen every possible take. People start posting "I am so tired of hearing about [the thing]" which is itself engagement with the thing. The platforms start serving it less because the engagement rate is dropping.

Stage six: the backlash to the backlash. Somebody posts "actually [the thing] was fine and everybody who had opinions about it was wrong." This gets traction for a day.

Stage seven: death. The thing is done. It still exists on the internet forever but nobody is talking about it. If you mention it six months from now, half the people you tell it to won't remember it.

Stage eight: revival. Two years later someone discovers it for the first time and posts it like it's new. The whole cycle runs again but shorter.

This is every viral moment ever. The specific content changes. The pattern doesn't. Knowing the pattern doesn't make you immune to it. You're going to get swept up in the next one anyway. We all are. But at least you'll recognize which stage you're in while it's happening.`,
